Musonius Rufus] Tacitus was ashamed to be thought a Stoic (see Agr. 4. 4), as elever men in France, and perhaps else- where, are ashamed to be thought orthodox‚ and so he has no objec- tion to laugh at a Stoic who lays himself open to ridicule. But Musonius was by no means a con- temptible man ; he was the master of EpictetuS‚ and is coupled with Socrates by Justin Martyr, in his first Apology, as an example of per- secuted virtue. He was a friend of Rubellius Plautus (Ann. xiv. 59. 2), and was banished by Nero (ib. xv. 71. 9), and, it is said, made to work as a convict on his Isthmian Canal.

Doubtless he returned on the fall of Nero. He was exempted by name from Vespasian's banishment of the philosophers, which seems to show that, like his great pupil, he abandoned political agitation for more spiritual objeets.
